In [2]:
def rmse(predictions, targets, **kwargs):
    return np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(targets, predictions))


def evaluate(model, test_features, test_labels):
    predictions = model.predict(test_features)
    errors = abs(predictions - test_labels)
    mape = 100 * np.mean(errors / test_labels)
    accuracy = 100 - mape
    print('Average Error: {:0.4f} degrees.'.format(np.mean(errors)))
    print('Accuracy = {:0.2f}%.'.format(accuracy))
    return accuracy
# src: https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/58391/mean-absolute-percentage-error-mape-in-scikit-learn


def mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred, **kwargs):
    y_true, y_pred = np.array(y_true), np.array(y_pred)
    return np.mean(np.abs((y_true - y_pred) / y_true)) * 100


# Create a custom scorer based on MAPE. This is used in GridSearchCV. Also
# used in sklearn, since that package does not offer MAPE as a scorer.
MAPE_SCORER = make_scorer(
    mean_absolute_percentage_error, greater_is_better=False)
MAE_SCORER = make_scorer(mean_absolute_error, greater_is_better=False)
RMSE_SCORER = make_scorer(rmse, greater_is_better=False)
MSE_SCORER = make_scorer(mean_squared_error, greater_is_better=False)
R2_SCORER = make_scorer(r2_score, greater_is_better=True)

In [90]:
num_folds = 10
kfold = KFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=1)

# Now we perform KFold:
# input_data = X
# target_data = Y

fold_num = 1
MAPE_train = []
MAPE_scores = []
RMSE_train = []
RMSE_scores = []
MAE_train = []
MAE_scores = []
R2_train = []
R2_scores = []
for train, test in kfold.split(X, Y):
    # This model's parameters were gathered using a brute-force loop. Shown further below.
    model = Sequential([
        Dense(1018, activation='relu', input_shape=(X.shape[1],)),
        Dense(1, activation='linear')
    ])
    model.compile(loss='mae', optimizer='adam', metrics=metrics)
    history = model.fit(
        X[train], Y[train], batch_size=128, epochs=1000, verbose=False)
    scores = model.evaluate(X[test], Y[test], verbose=False)
    predictions = model.predict(X[test])

    train_r2 = r2_score(Y[train], model.predict(X[train]))
    R2_train.append(train_r2)
    score_r2 = r2_score(Y[test], predictions)
    R2_scores.append(score_r2)
    MAPE_train.append(history.history.get(
        'mean_absolute_percentage_error')[-1])
    MAPE_scores.append(scores[2])
    RMSE_train.append(history.history.get('root_mean_squared_error')[-1])
    RMSE_scores.append(scores[1])
    MAE_train.append(history.history.get('loss')[-1])
    MAE_scores.append(scores[0])
    print(
        f"------------------------------------------Fold {fold_num}------------------------------------------")
    print(
        f"\tTrain Loss: {history.history.get('loss')[-1]}\tScore Loss: {scores[0]}")
    print(
        f"\tTrain RMSE: {history.history.get('root_mean_squared_error')[-1]}\tScore RMSE: {scores[1]}")
    print(
        f"\tTrain MAPE: {history.history.get('mean_absolute_percentage_error')[-1]}\tScore MAPE: {scores[2]}")
    print(f"\tTrain R2:   {train_r2}\tScore R2: {score_r2}")
    fold_num += 1


print(f"\n\nOverall MAE: {np.mean(MAE_scores)} +/- {np.std(MAE_scores)}")
print(f"Overall RMSE: {np.mean(RMSE_scores)} +/- {np.std(RMSE_scores)}")
print(f"Overall MAPE: {np.mean(MAPE_scores)} +/- {np.std(MAPE_scores)}")
print(f"Overall R2: {np.mean(R2_scores)*100} +/- {np.std(R2_scores)*100}\n\n")

print("Delimited table:")
print("MAPE\tRMSE\tMAE\tR2")
for i in range(0, 10):
    print("%.2f/%.2f\t%.2f/%.2f\t%.2f/%.2f\t%.2f/%.2f" %
          (MAPE_train[i], MAPE_scores[i], RMSE_train[i], RMSE_scores[i], MAE_train[i], MAE_scores[i], R2_train[i], R2_scores[i]))
print("%.2f/%.2f\t%.2f/%.2f\t%.2f/%.2f\t%.2f/%.2f\t<===Averages" % (np.mean(MAPE_train), np.mean(MAPE_scores),
      np.mean(RMSE_train), np.mean(RMSE_scores), np.mean(MAE_train), np.mean(MAE_scores), np.mean(R2_train), np.mean(R2_scores)))

Route 1: Use PCA for Dimensionality Reduction¶

First, we need to determine how many PCA components to use:¶

Method 1: Scree Plot¶

We can use a scree plot to determine how many components to reduce to.

src: https://towardsdatascience.com/a-one-stop-shop-for-principal-component-analysis-5582fb7e0a9c

In [76]:
pca_2 = PCA(n_components=45)
pca_2.fit_transform(X_data)
plt.plot(range(1, 46), pca_2.explained_variance_ratio_)
plt.ylabel("Explained Variance Ratio")
plt.xlabel("n_components")
plt.show()

The scree plot above shows an elbow right at the 5 components mark. This means we can get most of our information from 5 components.

Method 2: Threshold of Explained Variance Approach¶

We can also choose the number of PCA components based on the threshold of variance_explained approach, as shown below. In this case, the standard cumulative variance_explained to aim for is 70%, however we can see that even 1 component gets us 85% alone.

In [18]:
# threshold of variance explained approach. In this case, we hold on to principal components that explain at least 70%
# of the variance cumulatively
# https://www.datasklr.com/principal-component-analysis-and-factor-analysis/principal-component-analysis
print("Proportion of variance:")
print(pca_2.explained_variance_ratio_)
print("Cumulative variance:")
print(np.cumsum(pca_2.explained_variance_ratio_))

Method 3: Choosing A Variance Value Between 0.95 and 0.99¶

Here is our selected method. We have placed this method inside of a pipeline. This pipeline will scale the X data, as well as apply dimensionality reduction. The scaling of the data can be done via a minMaxScaler, or a StandardScaler().

In our case, PCA yields:

Variance n_components
0.95 18
0.99 25
In [19]:
n_components = 0.99

pipe = Pipeline([("scaler", StandardScaler()),
                ("pca", PCA(n_components=n_components))])

We Loop Through Possible Parameters to Generate A Shallow Neural Network¶

Since our dataset is small (~7000 samples), and the problem we tackling is multi-regression, we can try to brute force the solution.

According to Cybenko's Theorem, any continuous function can be approximated using a NN that has only one hidden layer.

We use this to our advantage, brute forcing the best NN parameters. Each run of this loop costs us about 9 hours in runtime, and objectively gives us the best parameters.

Later in this notebook, we find better results using deep learning networks.

In [21]:
# set up variables for next cell:
start_time = None
elapsed_time = None

# these dicts store parameters for the lowest value achieved for each metric:
rmse_dict = {'root_mean_squared_error': 10000000000}
mape_dict = {'mean_absolute_percentage_error': 10000000000}
mae_dict = {'mean_absolute_error': 10000000000}

# default learning rate for Adam is 0.001, maybe we can do a dynamic learning rate (lower as it goes).
learning_rate = 0.001
HL_1_nodes_max = 1024
activation_list = ['relu', 'linear']
loss_list = ['mse', 'mae']

metrics = [RootMeanSquaredError(), "mean_absolute_percentage_error",
           "mean_absolute_error"]

# num_inputs = X_train.shape[1]
In [22]:
def update_dict(x_dict, num_inputs, learning_rate, num_HL_nrns, HL1_ac_fn, HL2_ac_fn):
    x_dict['num_inputs'] = num_inputs
    x_dict['learning_rate'] = learning_rate
    x_dict['num_HL_nrns'] = num_HL_nrns
    x_dict['HL1_ac_fn'] = HL1_ac_fn
    x_dict['HL2_ac_fn'] = HL2_ac_fn
    x_dict['n_components'] = n_components


for num_HL_nrns in range(1, HL_1_nodes_max+1):
    if elapsed_time is not None:
        elapsed_time = elapsed_time*(HL_1_nodes_max-num_HL_nrns)
        print(
            f"\tTime Remaining: {int((elapsed_time//60)//60)}:{int((elapsed_time//60)%60)}:{int(elapsed_time%60)}", end="")
        print(
            f'\tETC: {time.strftime("%I:%Mp", time.localtime(time.time()+elapsed_time))}')
    start_time = time.process_time()

    for HL1_ac_fn in range(len(activation_list)):
        for HL2_ac_fn in range(len(activation_list)):
            for loss_fn in range(len(loss_list)):
                model = Sequential([
                    Dense(num_HL_nrns, activation=activation_list[HL1_ac_fn], input_shape=(
                        X_train.shape[1],)),
                    Dense(1, activation=activation_list[HL2_ac_fn])
                ])
                model.compile(loss=loss_list[loss_fn],
                              optimizer='adam', metrics=metrics)
                history = model.fit(X_train, Y_train, batch_size=128,
                                    verbose=False, epochs=100, validation_data=(X_test, Y_test))
                with open("rf_importance_models_logs.txt", "a") as file:
                    results = model.evaluate(X_test, Y_test, verbose=False)
                    file.write(
                        "\n++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++\n")
                    file.write(f"learning_rate: {learning_rate} ")
                    file.write(f"num_inputs: {num_inputs} ")
                    file.write(
                        f"num_HL_nrns: {num_HL_nrns} HL1_ac_fn: {activation_list[HL1_ac_fn]} ")
                    file.write(f"output_ac_fn: {activation_list[HL2_ac_fn]} ")
                    file.write(f"loss_fn: {loss_list[loss_fn]}\n")
                    # https://machinelearningmastery.com/display-deep-learning-model-training-history-in-keras/
                    for key in history.history.keys():
                        file.write(f"{key}: {history.history.get(key)[-1]}\n")
                    file.write("Evaluation:\n")
                    for i, metric in enumerate(model.metrics_names):
                        file.write(f"{metric}: {results[i]} ")
                if history.history.get('root_mean_squared_error')[-1] <= rmse_dict['root_mean_squared_error']:
                    rmse_dict['root_mean_squared_error'] = history.history.get(
                        'root_mean_squared_error')[-1]
                    update_dict(rmse_dict, num_inputs, learning_rate, num_HL_nrns,
                                activation_list[HL1_ac_fn], activation_list[HL2_ac_fn])
                if history.history.get('mean_absolute_percentage_error')[-1] <= mape_dict['mean_absolute_percentage_error']:
                    mape_dict['mean_absolute_percentage_error'] = history.history.get(
                        'mean_absolute_percentage_error')[-1]
                    update_dict(mape_dict, num_inputs, learning_rate, num_HL_nrns,
                                activation_list[HL1_ac_fn], activation_list[HL2_ac_fn])
                if history.history.get('mean_absolute_error')[-1] <= mae_dict['mean_absolute_error']:
                    mae_dict['mean_absolute_error'] = history.history.get(
                        'mean_absolute_error')[-1]
                    update_dict(mae_dict, num_inputs, learning_rate, num_HL_nrns,
                                activation_list[HL1_ac_fn], activation_list[HL2_ac_fn])
    elapsed_time = time.process_time() - start_time
    print(f"HL1 neurons {num_HL_nrns} done.", end="")

Our most important metric is Mean Absolute Percentage Error. Based on this, we can choose the SNN model that has the best MAPE. We then run 10-Fold Cross Validation to further test the generalizablity of the model, and to see if our model displayed any signs of overfitting.

In [24]:
num_folds = 10
kfold = KFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=1)

# Now we perform KFold:
# input_data = X
# target_data = Y

fold_num = 1
MAPE_train = []
MAPE_scores = []
RMSE_train = []
RMSE_scores = []
MAE_train = []
MAE_scores = []
R2_train = []
R2_scores = []
for train, test in kfold.split(X, Y):
    # we use the pipeline from earlier:
    train_piped = pipe.fit_transform(X[train])
    test_piped = pipe.transform(X[test])
    # now our data is ready to go into our model.
    model = Sequential([
        Dense(584, activation='relu', input_shape=(train_piped.shape[1],)),
        Dense(1, activation='relu')
    ])
    model.compile(loss='mae', optimizer='adam', metrics=metrics)
    history = model.fit(
        train_piped, Y[train], batch_size=128, epochs=1000, verbose=False)
    scores = model.evaluate(test_piped, Y[test], verbose=False)
    predictions = model.predict(test_piped)

    train_r2 = r2_score(Y[train], model.predict(train_piped))
    R2_train.append(train_r2)
    score_r2 = r2_score(Y[test], predictions)
    R2_scores.append(score_r2)
    MAPE_train.append(history.history.get(
        'mean_absolute_percentage_error')[-1])
    MAPE_scores.append(scores[2])
    RMSE_train.append(history.history.get('root_mean_squared_error')[-1])
    RMSE_scores.append(scores[1])
    MAE_train.append(history.history.get('loss')[-1])
    MAE_scores.append(scores[0])
    print(
        f"------------------------------------------Fold {fold_num}------------------------------------------")
    print(
        f"\tTrain Loss: {history.history.get('loss')[-1]}\tScore Loss: {scores[0]}")
    print(
        f"\tTrain RMSE: {history.history.get('root_mean_squared_error')[-1]}\tScore RMSE: {scores[1]}")
    print(
        f"\tTrain MAPE: {history.history.get('mean_absolute_percentage_error')[-1]}\tScore MAPE: {scores[2]}")
    print(f"\tTrain R2:   {train_r2}\tScore R2: {score_r2}")
    fold_num += 1


print(f"\n\nOverall MAE: {np.mean(MAE_scores)} +/- {np.std(MAE_scores)}")
print(f"Overall RMSE: {np.mean(RMSE_scores)} +/- {np.std(RMSE_scores)}")
print(f"Overall MAPE: {np.mean(MAPE_scores)} +/- {np.std(MAPE_scores)}")
print(f"Overall R2: {np.mean(R2_scores)*100} +/- {np.std(R2_scores)*100}\n\n")

print("Delimited table:")
print("MAPE\tRMSE\tMAE\tR2")
for i in range(0, 10):
    print("%.2f/%.2f\t%.2f/%.2f\t%.2f/%.2f\t%.2f/%.2f" %
          (MAPE_train[i], MAPE_scores[i], RMSE_train[i], RMSE_scores[i], MAE_train[i], MAE_scores[i], R2_train[i], R2_scores[i]))
print("%.2f/%.2f\t%.2f/%.2f\t%.2f/%.2f\t%.2f/%.2f\t<===Averages" % (np.mean(MAPE_train), np.mean(MAPE_scores),
      np.mean(RMSE_train), np.mean(RMSE_scores), np.mean(MAE_train), np.mean(MAE_scores), np.mean(R2_train), np.mean(R2_scores)))

num_folds = 10
kfold = KFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=1)

# Now we perform KFold:

fold_num = 1
MAPE_train = []
MAPE_scores = []
RMSE_train = []
RMSE_scores = []
MAE_train = []
MAE_scores = []
R2_train = []
R2_scores = []
for train, test in kfold.split(features_0_2_cutoff, Y):
    # now our data is ready to go into our model.
    model = Sequential([
        Dense(986, activation='relu', input_shape=(
            features_0_2_cutoff.shape[1],)),
        Dense(1, activation='relu')
    ])
    model.compile(loss='mae', optimizer='adam', metrics=metrics)
    history = model.fit(
        features_0_2_cutoff[train], Y[train], batch_size=128, epochs=1000, verbose=False)
    scores = model.evaluate(features_0_2_cutoff[test], Y[test], verbose=False)
    predictions = model.predict(features_0_2_cutoff[test])
    train_r2 = r2_score(Y[train], model.predict(features_0_2_cutoff[train]))
    R2_train.append(train_r2)
    score_r2 = r2_score(Y[test], predictions)
    R2_scores.append(score_r2)
    MAPE_train.append(history.history.get(
        'mean_absolute_percentage_error')[-1])
    MAPE_scores.append(scores[2])
    RMSE_train.append(history.history.get('root_mean_squared_error')[-1])
    RMSE_scores.append(scores[1])
    MAE_train.append(history.history.get('loss')[-1])
    MAE_scores.append(scores[0])

    print(
        f"------------------------------------------Fold {fold_num}------------------------------------------")
    print(
        f"\tTrain Loss: {history.history.get('loss')[-1]}\tScore Loss: {scores[0]}")
    print(
        f"\tTrain RMSE: {history.history.get('root_mean_squared_error')[-1]}\tScore RMSE: {scores[1]}")
    print(
        f"\tTrain MAPE: {history.history.get('mean_absolute_percentage_error')[-1]}\tScore MAPE: {scores[2]}")
    print(f"\tTrain R2:   {train_r2}\tScore R2: {score_r2}")
    fold_num += 1


print(f"\n\nOverall MAE: {np.mean(MAE_scores)} +/- {np.std(MAE_scores)}")

# Now we do 10fold cv for our NB:
num_folds = 10
kfold = KFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=1)

# Now we perform KFold:

fold_num = 1
NB_MAPE_train = []
NB_MAPE_scores = []
NB_RMSE_train = []
NB_RMSE_scores = []
NB_MAE_train = []
NB_MAE_scores = []
NB_R2_train = []
NB_R2_scores = []

# we split the entire dataframe:
for train, test in kfold.split(NB_df):
    NB_CV_model = smf.glm(
        formula_str, data=NB_df.iloc[train], family=sm.families.NegativeBinomial()).fit()

    train_predictions = NB_CV_model.predict(NB_df.iloc[train])
    test_predictions = NB_CV_model.predict(NB_df.iloc[test])
    train_mae = mean_absolute_error(
        NB_df.iloc[train]['DailyVolume'], train_predictions)
    NB_MAE_train.append(train_mae)
    test_mae = mean_absolute_error(
        NB_df.iloc[test]['DailyVolume'], test_predictions)
    NB_MAE_scores.append(test_mae)
    train_rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(
        NB_df.iloc[train]['DailyVolume'], train_predictions))
    NB_RMSE_train.append(train_rmse)
    test_rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(
        NB_df.iloc[test]['DailyVolume'], test_predictions))
    NB_RMSE_scores.append(test_rmse)
    train_mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(
        NB_df.iloc[train]['DailyVolume'], train_predictions)
    NB_MAPE_train.append(train_mape)
    test_mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(
        NB_df.iloc[test]['DailyVolume'], test_predictions)
    NB_MAPE_scores.append(test_mape)
    train_r2 = r2_score(NB_df.iloc[train]['DailyVolume'], train_predictions)
    NB_R2_train.append(train_r2)
    score_r2 = r2_score(NB_df.iloc[test]['DailyVolume'], test_predictions)
    NB_R2_scores.append(score_r2)
    print(
        f"------------------------------------------Fold {fold_num}------------------------------------------")
    print(f"\tTrain MAE: {train_mae}\tScore Loss: {test_mae}")
    print(f"\tTrain RMSE: {train_rmse}\tScore RMSE: {test_rmse}")
    print(f"\tTrain MAPE: {train_mape}\tScore MAPE: {test_mape}")
    print(f"\tTrain R2:   {train_r2}\tScore R2: {score_r2}")
    fold_num += 1

print(f"\n\nOverall MAE: {np.mean(NB_MAE_scores)} +/- {np.std(NB_MAE_scores)}")
print(f"Overall RMSE: {np.mean(NB_RMSE_scores)} +/- {np.std(NB_RMSE_scores)}")
print(f"Overall MAPE: {np.mean(NB_MAPE_scores)} +/- {np.std(NB_MAPE_scores)}")
print(
    f"Overall R2: {np.mean(NB_R2_scores)*100} +/- {np.std(NB_R2_scores)*100}\n\n")

# Hyperparameter tunning for Xgboost

# Number of trees to be used
xgb_n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(200, 2000, 10)]

# Maximum number of levels in tree
xgb_max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(10, 110, 11)]

# Minimum number of instaces needed in each node
xgb_min_child_weight = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(1, 10, 10)]

# Tree construction algorithm used in XGBoost
xgb_tree_method = ['auto', 'exact', 'approx', 'hist', 'gpu_hist']

# Learning rate
xgb_eta = [x for x in np.linspace(0.1, 0.6, 6)]

# Minimum loss reduction required to make further partition
xgb_gamma = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(0, 0.5, 6)]

# Learning objective used
xgb_objective = ['reg:squarederror', 'reg:squaredlogerror']

# Create the grid

            'max_depth': xgb_max_depth,

# Define a function that compares all final models
def final_comparison(models, test_features, test_labels):
    scores = pd.DataFrame()
    for model in models:
        predictions = model.predict(test_features)
        mae = round(mean_absolute_error(test_labels, predictions), 4)
        rmse = round(np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(test_labels, predictions)), 4)
        r2 = round(r2_score(test_labels, predictions), 4)
        errors = abs(predictions - test_labels)
        mape = 100 * np.mean(errors / test_labels)
        accuracy = round(100 - mape, 4)
        scores[str(model)] = [mae, rmse, r2, mape, accuracy]
    scores.index = ['Mean Absolute Error', 'Root Mean Squared Error',
                    'R^2', 'Mean Absolute Percentage Error', 'Accuracy']
    return scores

for train, test in kfold.split(XGB_X_data, XGB_Y_data):
    # now our data is ready to go into our model.
    model = Sequential([
        Dense(823, activation='relu', input_shape=(XGB_X_data.shape[1],)),
        Dense(1, activation='linear')
    ])
    model.compile(loss='mae', optimizer='adam', metrics=metrics)
    history = model.fit(
        XGB_X_data[train], XGB_Y_data[train], batch_size=128, epochs=1000, verbose=False)
    scores = model.evaluate(XGB_X_data[test], XGB_Y_data[test], verbose=False)
    train_r2 = r2_score(XGB_Y_data[train], model.predict(XGB_X_data[train]))
    XGB_R2_train.append(train_r2)
    score_r2 = r2_score(XGB_Y_data[test], model.predict(XGB_X_data[test]))
    XGB_R2_scores.append(score_r2)
    XGB_MAPE_train.append(history.history.get(
        'mean_absolute_percentage_error')[-1])
    XGB_MAPE_scores.append(scores[2])
    XGB_RMSE_train.append(history.history.get('root_mean_squared_error')[-1])

    train_mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(Y[train], train_predictions)
    lr_MAPE_train.append(train_mape)

    train_rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(Y[train], train_predictions))

    # we split the Y[test] into 3 inclusive volumes: low (0-299), medium (300-750), high (>= 751)
    low_Y_test_mask = np.all([Y[test] >= 0, Y[test] <=299], axis=0)
    med_Y_test_mask = np.all([Y[test] >= 300, Y[test] <=750], axis=0)
    high_Y_test_mask = np.all([Y[test] >= 751],axis=0)
    
    lr_low_MAPE_scores.append(mean_absolute_percentage_error(Y[test][low_Y_test_mask], lr_CV_model.predict(X[test][low_Y_test_mask])))
    lr_low_RMSE_scores.append(math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(Y[test][low_Y_test_mask], lr_CV_model.predict(X[test][low_Y_test_mask]))))
    lr_low_MAE_scores.append(mean_absolute_error(Y[test][low_Y_test_mask], lr_CV_model.predict(X[test][low_Y_test_mask])))
    lr_low_R2_scores.append(r2_score(Y[test][low_Y_test_mask], lr_CV_model.predict(X[test][low_Y_test_mask])))

    lr_med_MAPE_scores.append(mean_absolute_percentage_error(Y[test][med_Y_test_mask], lr_CV_model.predict(X[test][med_Y_test_mask])))
    lr_med_RMSE_scores.append(math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(Y[test][med_Y_test_mask], lr_CV_model.predict(X[test][med_Y_test_mask]))))
    lr_med_MAE_scores.append(mean_absolute_error(Y[test][med_Y_test_mask], lr_CV_model.predict(X[test][med_Y_test_mask])))
    lr_med_R2_scores.append(r2_score(Y[test][med_Y_test_mask], lr_CV_model.predict(X[test][med_Y_test_mask])))

    lr_high_MAPE_scores.append(mean_absolute_percentage_error(Y[test][high_Y_test_mask], lr_CV_model.predict(X[test][high_Y_test_mask])))
    lr_high_RMSE_scores.append(math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(Y[test][high_Y_test_mask], lr_CV_model.predict(X[test][high_Y_test_mask]))))
    lr_high_MAE_scores.append(mean_absolute_error(Y[test][high_Y_test_mask], lr_CV_model.predict(X[test][high_Y_test_mask])))
    lr_high_R2_scores.append(r2_score(Y[test][med_Y_test_mask], lr_CV_model.predict(X[test][med_Y_test_mask])))

    print(
        f"------------------------------------------Fold {fold_num}------------------------------------------")
    print(f"\tTrain MAE: {train_mae}\tScore Loss: {test_mae}")
    print(f"\tTrain RMSE: {train_rmse}\tScore RMSE: {test_rmse}")
    print(f"\tTrain MAPE: {train_mape}\tScore MAPE: {test_mape}")
    print(f"\tTrain R2:   {train_r2}\tScore R2: {score_r2}")
    print(f"\n\t3-VOLUME SCORES: LOW (n={Y[test][low_Y_test_mask].shape[0]}), MED (n={Y[test][med_Y_test_mask].shape[0]}), HIGH (n={Y[test][high_Y_test_mask].shape[0]}), TOTAL IN FOLD (n={test.shape[0]})")
    print(f"\tLow Loss: {lr_low_MAE_scores[-1]}\tMed Loss: {lr_med_MAE_scores[-1]}\tHigh Loss: {lr_high_MAE_scores[-1]}")
    print(f"\tLow RMSE: {lr_low_RMSE_scores[-1]}\tMed RMSE: {lr_med_RMSE_scores[-1]}\tHigh RMSE: {lr_high_RMSE_scores[-1]}")

Doing 10-Fold CV Using Linear Regression On Features Selected By Random Forest¶

Since linear regression is the simplest method to solving a multivariate regression problem, we decided to test its performance on the imporant variables (previously selected by our Random Forest model). We chose the same importance cutoff as before, Importance > 0.02.

In [67]:
LR_RF_FS_X_data = np.asarray(data_filled.drop(_0_2_cutoff, axis=1))

# Now we do 10fold cv for our NB:
num_folds = 10
kfold = KFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=1)

# Now we perform KFold:

fold_num = 1
lr_MAPE_train = []
lr_MAPE_scores = []
lr_RMSE_train = []
lr_RMSE_scores = []
lr_MAE_train = []
lr_MAE_scores = []
lr_R2_train = []
lr_R2_scores = []

# we split the entire dataframe:
for train, test in kfold.split(LR_RF_FS_X_data, Y):
    lr_rf_fs_CV_model = LinearRegression().fit(
        LR_RF_FS_X_data[train], Y[train])
    train_predictions = lr_rf_fs_CV_model.predict(LR_RF_FS_X_data[train])
    test_predictions = lr_rf_fs_CV_model.predict(LR_RF_FS_X_data[test])
    train_mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(Y[train], train_predictions)
    lr_MAPE_train.append(train_mape)
    test_mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(Y[test], test_predictions)
    lr_MAPE_scores.append(test_mape)
    train_rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(Y[train], train_predictions))
    lr_RMSE_train.append(train_rmse)
    test_rmse = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(Y[test], test_predictions))
    lr_RMSE_scores.append(test_rmse)
    train_mae = mean_absolute_error(Y[train], train_predictions)
    lr_MAE_train.append(train_mae)
    test_mae = mean_absolute_error(Y[test], test_predictions)
    lr_MAE_scores.append(test_mae)
    train_r2 = r2_score(Y[train], train_predictions)
    lr_R2_train.append(train_r2)
    score_r2 = r2_score(Y[test], test_predictions)
    lr_R2_scores.append(score_r2)
    print(
        f"------------------------------------------Fold {fold_num}------------------------------------------")
    print(f"\tTrain MAE: {train_mae}\tScore Loss: {test_mae}")
    print(f"\tTrain RMSE: {train_rmse}\tScore RMSE: {test_rmse}")
    print(f"\tTrain MAPE: {train_mape}\tScore MAPE: {test_mape}")
    print(f"\tTrain R2:   {train_r2}\tScore R2: {score_r2}")
    fold_num += 1

print(f"\n\nOverall MAE: {np.mean(lr_MAE_scores)} +/- {np.std(lr_MAE_scores)}")
